ce:section.ce:para:
The water-soluble NS-CDs were created using green, microwave-aided pyrolysis in a home microwave in only 90 s (Scheme 1
                        ) since microwave-assisted heating improves reaction rates and reduces energy consumption [36]. In addition, the characteristics of microwave heating increases PY which was observed in the prepared CDs’ high PY of 54.27 wt percent. The blue luminous NS-CDs were created using simple method and available starting ingredients; glucose as carbon supply and l-cysteine as sulfur/nitrogen supply. In order to optimize the probe for TLM determination, various glucose to l-cysteine ratios were tested (Fig. S1), and the molar ratio of 6 mmol glucose: 1 mmol l-cysteine was chosen as the optimum ratio since it produced the best interaction with TLM. Fig. S2 displays the optical picture of the NS-CDs solution in both natural and UV light. When exposed to UV light, the produced NS-CDs fluoresced blue and maintained their fluorescence over a period of three weeks. The produced CDs showed small size range of 1–3 nm and were found to be uniformly distributed quasispherical particles without obvious aggregation, according to TEM images (Fig. 1
                        A). The HRTEM pictures of the particles' lattice fringes (Fig. 1B) reveal crystallinity of NS-CDs, and lattice spacing was determined to be 0.29 nm, which corresponds to (110) basal plane distance of the bulk graphite [37]. SAED pattern provided additional confirmation of the crystallinity (Fig. 1C). The pattern presented a diffraction ring structure which was composed of bright spots arranged in concentric circular patterns indicating polycrystalline arrangements of NS-CDs [38]. The composition of NS-CDs was determined using elemental analysis employing EDX, and it was found that NS-CDs comprised of C (90.47%), O (5.64%), N (2.01%), and S (1.88%) (Fig. S3) indicating successful doping. The following peaks (cm−1) were found when the surface groups were analyzed using FTIR (Fig. S4), including N–H (3448 and 3420), O–H (3420, broad), S–H (2620). These functional groups could improve the hydrophilicity and stability of the CDs in aqueous system [39]. The bands of CO (1739) and C–O (1153/1016) indicated the presence of carboxylic acid and other oxygen-containing functional groups [40]. Furthermore, N–H bending (1649) and C–N (1262) suggested the existence of amino-containing functional groups, and CC (1430) indicated unsaturated/aromatic system [41]. The CDs' optical properties were investigated using the UV spectrum (Fig. 2
                        ), which showed that they feature two peaks at 227 and 283 nm that match π-π* transitions and one peak at 335 nm that corresponds to n-π* transitions [42,43]. Excitation dependence was visible in the emission of synthesized CDs in the 290–390 nm region (Fig. S5). After 350 nm excitation, the peak fluorescence emission occurred at 416 nm (QY of 5.6%). The NS-CDs' fluorescence was directly proportional to their concentration, which ranged from 0.07 to 0.23 mg/mL.

Interfering materials such as lactose, ascorbic acid, Ca2+, Mg2+, Fe2+, Co2+, PO4
                        3−, and propylene glycol were examined to evaluate reliability of the proposed probe (Fig. 6
                        ). Common species in pharmaceutical samples and milk were shown to exhibit negligible influence on TLM determination. Furthermore, the selectivity of the fluorescent probe towards TLM detection was tested in the presence of some structurally related compounds (erythromycin and tylosin) and veterinary antibiotics (tiamulin). The tolerance limit of these drugs was established as the concentration that causes 2% relative error [56], which was found to be 16.4, 17.5, 30.0 μM for tiamulin, tylosin, and erythromycin, respectively. The method was validated following ICH Q2 (R1) recommendations [57]. The acceptable% recovery, which is displayed in Table S1, served as evidence for the method's accuracy over the studied concentration range. Low inter-day and intra-day % RSD values shown in Table S2 reveal the proposed method's high degree of precision.
